403→                    
404→                           This would be best possible, for example letting $A=[1,N/2]\cap \mathbb{N}$ and $B=\{ N/2&lt;p\leq N: p\textrm{ prime}\}$. <br><br>This is true, and was proved by Szemerédi <a href="#cite-Sz76-490" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Sz76','490'); return false;">[Sz76]</a>.<br><br>In <a href="#cite-Er72-490" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er72','490'); return false;">[Er72]</a> Erdős goes on to ask whether\[\lim_{N\to \infty}\max_{A,B\subseteq [N]}\frac{\lvert A\rvert\lvert B\rvert\log N}{N^2}\]exists, where the maximum is over $A$ and $B$ with all the products $ab$ distinct, and to determine its value. As noted in the comments to <a href="/896" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[896]</a> by van Doorn, if the limit exists it must be $\geq 1$.<br><br>See also <a href="/425" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[425]</a> and <a href="/896" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[896]</a>.
